# Data Analysis 

Across all treatments, survival remained high and relatively similar, with most individuals living to the end of the experiment, indicating that the treatment did not strongly affect mortality. However, reproduction showed clear differences among treatments, with the control (0 ppm) having the highest and most consistent reproductive output, while higher concentrations (especially 10 ppm) showed reduced and more variable reproduction. The timing of reproduction also shifted, as individuals in higher treatments tended to reproduce later and less consistently, which was evident in the lx·mx plots. These changes in both the amount and timing of reproduction led to lower net reproductive rates (R₀) and reduced intrinsic growth rates (r) in higher treatments. Overall, the results show that the treatment has a sublethal effect, primarily impacting reproduction and population growth rather than survival.
